******
[2]
Date: Wed 21 Oct 2015
Source: Globo Noticias [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.RNA, edited]
http://g1.globo.com/pr/norte-noroeste/noticia/2015/10/vigilancia-sanitaria-investiga-surto-de-toxoplasmose-no-iapar-em-londrina.html


Seventeen workers of the Agronomic Institute of Parana (IAPAR) of Londrina, in [northern Parana state], acquired toxoplasmosis, according to Health Surveillance Office, investigating an outbreak at the site this week.

It is suspected that the water or food served to the workers were contaminated but so far tests have not identified the source of contamination. Since the outbreak was discovered, workers have received lectures on prevention and treatment and hygiene at the institute has been reinforced. Work at the institute continues and those who are ill are receiving treatment and responding well.

Experts say the contamination happened between July and August [2015], but symptoms appeared only in recent weeks. The infected workers are being treated at the institute's outpatient clinic. The disease was only discovered after an employee sought help from a doctor outside the institute.

"[Symptoms include] body ache, fever, and headache. In the beginning we mistook it for conventional influenza. Then one employee tested positive for toxoplasmosis. After that we started to investigate to find the source of the infection," explained nurse trainee, Francislaine Mateus da Silva.

One of the infected workers said the 1st doctor who examined him mistook the disease with influenza A. "I had fever for about 3 or 4 days and I took Tamiflu [oseltamivir], which the doctor prescribed. Later, the result was positive for toxoplasmosis."

Cassia Balbinotti, benefits manager for IAPAR, said, "the institute has outside suppliers and they are all being investigated. We are reviewing the routine guidelines, such as recommended hygiene practices for both the restaurant workers and the other institute employees."

