[We assume that the diagnosis of toxoplasmosis is correct even though the text does not mention anything about the results of the serology.

Waterborne outbreaks of toxoplasmosis are well known. The best described happened in Victoria, Vancouver Island (Canada) in 1994-95 when a water reservoir was contaminated by _Toxoplasma gondii_ oocysts presumably from wild cougars defecating in the reservoir.

Other outbreaks have been reported from Brazil. Surface water is contaminated by _T. gondii_ oocysts from defecating cats, and if the water is consumed without cooking or swallowed for instance when swimming, there is a risk of infection.

Infection with toxoplasma causes a short febrile illness in the majority of cases, but is more severe in 10-15 per cent, especially causing choroiditis (retinal inflammation). In pregnant women it may cause congenital toxoplasmosis and the infection is more severe in the immunocompromised, for instance HIV-positive patients. - Mod.EP

Maps of Brazil can be seen at http://s13.postimg.org/jumnalk87/map_of_Brazil.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3773850,9511. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
